# 05_resolver_translates — proof the listener tries long-name resolution.
#
# The DB at /com/curvz/app/data/widget_names.db has 386 rows; one of
# them is:
#
#   tb_nod    main_toolbar_node_tool_btn    src/Toolbar.cpp:786
#
# This script asks for `main_toolbar_node_tool_btn` — a long_name in
# the DB. The listener's resolver translates it to the abbrev `tb_nod`
# and looks `tb_nod` up in the registry. The registry doesn't have
# `tb_nod` (because the Node tool button registered under the hand-
# picked name `tool.node`, not under its widget_names.db abbrev), so
# the listener reports unknown — BUT critically, the error message
# describes the resolved abbrev, not the input. That's the proof.
#
# Expected output:
#
#   > main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
#   error unknown object 'main_toolbar_node_tool_btn' (did you mean
#     'tool.node'?)
#
# The suggestion happens because closest_name_across_columns considers
# the live registry (which has `tool.node`) alongside the DB columns.
#
# After the funnel migration registers all toolbar buttons under their
# abbrevs, this same script will instead PASS — `tb_nod` will be a
# real registry entry, the long_name will resolve, and the click will
# fire. That's the through-line: same script, two outcomes across the
# milestone boundary.

main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
